---
import BaseLayout from '../../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
const title = 'Common Sexual Harassment Claim Misconceptions | SexualHarassmentCalc';
const description = 'Fifteen widespread myths about workplace sexual harassment claims corrected against the actual statute and case law.';
---
<BaseLayout title={title} description={description}>
  <h1>Common Sexual Harassment Claim Misconceptions</h1>
  <p><em>Reviewed by Devin Bertram (DB), Editor-in-Chief &mdash; EEOC Practice. Updated May 2026.</em></p>

  <p>
    Fifteen widespread misconceptions about workplace sexual harassment claims, each corrected against the actual statute, the
    EEOC&rsquo;s position, and controlling Supreme Court authority. These come from intake calls, severance negotiations, and
    HR-policy boilerplate that has been wrong for years.
  </p>

  <h2>1. &ldquo;Harassment has to be physical to count.&rdquo;</h2>
  <p>
    False. Under <em>Harris v. Forklift Systems, Inc.</em>, 510 U.S. 17 (1993), a hostile work environment can be created by verbal
    conduct alone &mdash; repeated propositions, sexual jokes, comments about the employee&rsquo;s body, displays of sexual material,
    pet names with sexual undertones. The question is whether the conduct, viewed in totality, is severe or pervasive enough to
    alter the conditions of employment. Physical contact is not required.
  </p>

  <h2>2. &ldquo;You have to report immediately or you lose the claim.&rdquo;</h2>
  <p>
    False. There is no immediate-reporting requirement in Title VII. The relevant deadlines are the EEOC charge deadlines
    (180/300 days from the last act, with continuing-violation doctrine available in hostile-environment cases) and the state
    statutes of limitations. Delayed reporting can support an employer&rsquo;s <em>Faragher</em>/<em>Ellerth</em> defense in supervisor
    cases without tangible action, but a documented reason for the delay (fear of retaliation, the harasser&rsquo;s position in
    the complaint chain, prior ignored complaints) neutralizes that.
  </p>

  <h2>3. &ldquo;You have to use HR before going to the EEOC.&rdquo;</h2>
  <p>
    False. There is no exhaustion-of-internal-remedies requirement under Title VII. You can file an EEOC charge without ever
    having complained to HR. Failure to use a reasonable, communicated internal complaint procedure can help the employer&rsquo;s
    affirmative defense in supervisor hostile-environment cases without tangible action, which is why most plaintiffs do file an
    internal complaint in writing &mdash; but it is a strategic decision, not a jurisdictional prerequisite.
  </p>

  <h2>4. &ldquo;The plaintiff&rsquo;s prior sexual conduct is fair game at trial.&rdquo;</h2>
  <p>
    Largely false. Federal Rule of Evidence 412 (the &ldquo;rape shield&rdquo; rule for civil cases) restricts evidence of a sexual
    harassment plaintiff&rsquo;s sexual behavior or sexual predisposition. The court can admit such evidence only if its probative
    value substantially outweighs the danger of harm to the plaintiff and unfair prejudice, and the party offering it must follow
    the procedural notice provisions. The default is exclusion, not admission. Many states have parallel evidence rules.
  </p>

  <h2>5. &ldquo;If federal law applies, state law doesn&rsquo;t.&rdquo;</h2>
  <p>
    False. State fair-employment statutes are independent claims, not preempted by Title VII. In states with stronger statutes
    (California FEHA, NY HRL, NJ LAD, IL HRA, MA c. 151B), the state claim often drives case value because it has no damages cap,
    a longer statute of limitations, or lower employee-count thresholds for coverage. Most plaintiff&rsquo;s lawyers plead both
    federal and state theories and let the case proceed under whichever is more favorable.
  </p>

  <h2>6. &ldquo;A single incident can never be a hostile work environment.&rdquo;</h2>
  <p>
    False. <em>Harris v. Forklift</em>&rsquo;s &ldquo;severe or pervasive&rdquo; standard is disjunctive. A single act of sexual
    assault, a single supervisor demand backed by threat of termination, or a single incident of extreme physical or verbal
    conduct can satisfy the standard on its own. Most cases still rely on a course of conduct, but the law does not require it.
  </p>

  <h2>7. &ldquo;Coworker harassment carries the same liability rules as supervisor harassment.&rdquo;</h2>
  <p>
    False. The rules differ. Supervisor harassment with a tangible employment action triggers strict vicarious liability with no
    affirmative defense (<em>Ellerth</em>). Supervisor harassment without a tangible action allows the <em>Faragher</em>/<em>Ellerth</em>
    affirmative defense. Coworker harassment is evaluated on a negligence standard &mdash; the employer is liable only if it knew
    or should have known and failed to take prompt remedial action. The plaintiff&rsquo;s leverage in supervisor cases is much higher.
  </p>

  <h2>8. &ldquo;Settlement amounts are predictable from public verdicts.&rdquo;</h2>
  <p>
    False. Public jury verdicts are a biased sample &mdash; they capture only cases that did not settle, which is fewer than 5%
    of filed harassment cases and a tiny fraction of charged cases. Most settlements are confidential or settled before public
    filing. Public databases also overweight outliers in both directions. The realistic range for an individual case depends on
    employer size, jurisdiction, evidence, claim theory, and the specific defendants&rsquo; trial posture &mdash; not on the
    headline numbers.
  </p>

  <h2>9. &ldquo;Settlement payments are tax-free because they&rsquo;re for emotional distress.&rdquo;</h2>
  <p>
    False, and a frequent unpleasant surprise. Under 26 U.S.C. &sect; 104(a)(2), only damages received on account of <em>physical</em>
    injury or sickness are excluded from gross income. Emotional-distress damages without an underlying physical injury are
    taxable. Back pay and front pay are taxable as wages. Punitive damages are taxable. Section 162(q) added in 2017 also denies
    employers a tax deduction for harassment settlements subject to confidentiality, which shifts negotiation incentives.
  </p>

  <h2>10. &ldquo;An NDA in the settlement means nobody can ever talk about what happened.&rdquo;</h2>
  <p>
    Less true than it used to be. The <strong>Speak Out Act of 2022</strong> (42 U.S.C. &sect; 19401 et seq.) voids pre-dispute
    nondisclosure and non-disparagement clauses covering sexual harassment or sexual assault disputes. Many states (CA, NY, NJ,
    IL, others) have voided post-dispute NDAs that prevent disclosure of the underlying conduct, with carve-outs for the
    settlement amount. Employees can usually still discuss the conduct with attorneys, regulators, and law enforcement regardless
    of contract language.
  </p>

  <h2>11. &ldquo;At-will employment means I can be fired for any reason after complaining.&rdquo;</h2>
  <p>
    False. At-will employment means either side can end the relationship at any time for any reason that is not unlawful. Firing
    you for filing or supporting a sexual harassment complaint is unlawful retaliation under 42 U.S.C. &sect; 2000e-3(a) and
    parallel state law. Retaliation claims are often the strongest part of a harassment case precisely because temporal proximity
    between complaint and adverse action is usually well-documented.
  </p>

  <h2>12. &ldquo;Only women can bring sexual harassment claims.&rdquo;</h2>
  <p>
    False. Title VII is sex-neutral. <em>Oncale v. Sundowner Offshore Services, Inc.</em>, 523 U.S. 75 (1998), confirmed that
    same-sex harassment is actionable. <em>Bostock v. Clayton County</em>, 590 U.S. 644 (2020), confirmed that sex discrimination
    includes discrimination based on sexual orientation and gender identity. Male, female, and nonbinary employees can bring
    claims; LGBTQ employees harassed because of orientation or gender identity are covered.
  </p>

  <h2>13. &ldquo;The employer isn&rsquo;t liable if HR investigates and fires the harasser.&rdquo;</h2>
  <p>
    Partly true, partly false. A prompt, effective remedial response can defeat liability for <em>future</em> harassment and can
    support the <em>Faragher</em>/<em>Ellerth</em> defense in supervisor cases without tangible action. It does not retroactively
    erase the harassment that already occurred, the harm the plaintiff already suffered, or any retaliation that followed the
    complaint. &ldquo;We fired the guy&rdquo; is a defense to ongoing claims, not a discharge of past liability.
  </p>

  <h2>14. &ldquo;If the harasser was a customer, not an employee, the company is off the hook.&rdquo;</h2>
  <p>
    False. Under 29 C.F.R. &sect; 1604.11(e) and EEOC guidance, employers can be liable for harassment by non-employees &mdash;
    customers, vendors, clients, patients &mdash; where the employer knew or should have known and failed to take prompt,
    appropriate remedial action within its control. Restaurant, healthcare, retail, and field-sales workers regularly have these
    claims. The employer&rsquo;s remedies are narrower (it cannot fire a customer&rsquo;s employee) but the duty to act on its own
    side of the relationship remains.
  </p>

  <h2>15. &ldquo;Filing a charge will make me unemployable in the industry.&rdquo;</h2>
  <p>
    Mostly false in 2026, though the fear is real. Title VII protects against retaliation by the current employer; some states
    (California Labor Code &sect; 432.7, NY Labor Law &sect; 201-f, and others) extend protections against blacklisting and
    require former employers to provide neutral references after a settled harassment claim. Background-check companies operate
    under FCRA constraints. Many industries have changed materially post-#MeToo. Talk to a lawyer about the specific industry
    risk in your state before letting the fear of retaliation override the deadline to file.
  </p>

  <h2>Closing note</h2>
  <p>
    Misconceptions like these are how plaintiffs lose leverage they did not need to lose &mdash; signing an unnecessary release,
    missing a deadline, or failing to document because they thought the rules required something they don&rsquo;t. If any of these
    surprised you, that is the signal to talk to an employment plaintiff&rsquo;s attorney before making decisions on your case.
  </p>
</BaseLayout>
